04598nam a22006615i 9781526139153DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815261391537 a10.7765/97815261391532doi  a(DE-B1597)660120  a(OCoLC)1153310392  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 7aPOL0580002bisacsh04a341.242209412231 aSteven, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) :bPolitics, parties and policies /cMartin Steven. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b3 black & white illustrations; 10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Perspectives on the Right ;v1300tFront matter -- tDedication -- tContents -- tList of figures -- tList of tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of abbreviations -- t1 The European Conservatives and Reformists parliamentary group -- tThe European Conservatives and Reformists parliamentary group -- t2 The British Conservative Party and the development of ECR -- t3 Euro-realism -- t4 Member parties of the European Conservatives and Reformists -- t5 ECR politicians and leadership structures -- t6 ECR policy activities in the European Parliament -- t7 Conclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) are now established as one of the larger groups in the European Parliament and from 2014 to 2019 had more MEPs than the Liberals, Greens or radical left and right-wing factions. Despite this, ECR has so far been largely dismissed by political scientists, journalists and Brussels policy-makers as merely another Euro-sceptic faction. Representing the first major study of the political activities of ECR and its ‘Euro-realist’ agenda, this book argues that ECR ought to be recognised as the main voice for Conservatism in Strasbourg, promoting ‘Anglosphere’ free market values and the role of NATO in international relations.The book begins with an examination of the origins and early development of ECR, when British Conservative leader David Cameron established the group in a Euro-sceptic gesture to his party. Cameron failed, however, to see the isolating long-term consequences of withdrawing his MEPs from the powerful European People’s Party (EPP).Other chapters examine the role of ECR member parties in its development and profile – including Law and Justice (PiS) from Poland, the Czech Civic Democrats (ODS), the New Flemish Alliance (N-VA) and the Danish People’s Party (DF). Drawing on interviews with MEPs and other key figures, the book concludes with an analysis of the leadership and policy activities of ECR politicians in Brussels and Strasbourg in an attempt to measure influence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConservatismzEuropexHistoryy21st century. 0aPolitical partieszEuropean Union countriesxInfluence. 0aSkepticismxPolitical aspects. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / European.2bisacsh  aAtlanticism.  aBrexit.  aConservatism.  aEuro-realism.  aEurope.  aParliament.  aParties.  aPoland.  aPolitics.  aStrasbourg.1 aSteven, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613915340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526139153423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526139153/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles